Mexican Stocks: Aeroportuario Pacifico, Homex, Penoles, Telmex

-- B y   L e o n   L a z a r o f f
-- 
2011-05-31T21:15:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/mexican-stocks-aeroportuario-del-pacifico-telefonos-de-mexico.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in Mexico trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time.  The IPC index rose 0.5 percent to 35,832.79.  Grupo Aeroportuario del Pacifico SAB (GAPB MM) advanced 2.4
percent to 47.28 pesos as the operator of airports in the
Pacific and central regions of Mexico said it obtained a  credit
line  of 1.02 billion pesos ($88.2 million) for airports in five
Mexican cities. The credit line from HSBC Holdings Plc will be
used to finance investments in the airports this year and in
2012, the company said today in a statement to Mexico’s stock
exchange.  Desarrolladora Homex SAB (HOMEX* MM), Mexico’s largest
homebuilder, climbed 3.1 percent to 45.67 pesos, its biggest
one-day increase in almost a month, as the peso rose to its
strongest against the dollar in three weeks. Before today, Homex
shares had fallen 37 percent this year.  Industrias Penoles SAB (PE&OLES* MM), Mexico’s second-
largest mining company, gained 3 percent to 450.54 pesos as
silver rallied. Silver futures for July delivery rose 61.7
cents, or 1.6 percent, to $38.48 an ounce.  Telefonos de  Mexico  SAB (TELMEXL MM), the nation’s largest
phone carrier, gained 2.1 percent to 10.38 pesos a day after
falling the most since December 2008 after the government
rejected its application to start offering video services.
Telmex, as the Mexico City-based company is known, said it would
appeal the Communications and Transportation Ministry’s
decision. Telmex shares fell 6.4 percent yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
